library(ComMA)

Box Whiskers plot

Load the example data model.test, and display the first 3 rows:

data(model.test)
model.test[1:3,]
##   model test performance  OS
## 1   GTR 1044    1.144838 Mac
## 2   GTR 1366    1.081676 Mac
## 3   GTR 1510    1.078596 Mac

Plot all performance scores for four GTR models, where each box is the statistical summary of the test:

ggBoxWhiskersPlot(model.test, x.id="test", y.id="performance", colour.id="OS", x.text.angle=90, verbose = F)

Adjust view

Zoom in the plot in y-axis without change the underlying data using y.lim.cart=c(NA,5), where the lower bound is not changed by given NA.

ggBoxWhiskersPlot(model.test, x.id="test", y.id="performance", colour.id="OS", 
                  x.text.angle=90, y.lim.cart=c(NA,5), verbose = F)

Histogram

This plots a 1d distribution by dividing performance into bins and counting the number of observations in each bin.

ggHistogram(model.test[model.test$performance<3,], x.id="performance", fill.id="model", 
            binwidth=0.1, x.text.angle=90, verbose=F)

Heatmap

Load the example data reads.phyla, where x is one of genetic marks, and the numbers are eDNA sequences (reads) identified as the phylum listed in y. Remove any column which will be not used, but add phylum column for labelling heatmap y-axis. Sort data by row sums and only select the most 20 abundant phyla from 6 genetic markers.

data(reads.phyla)
#reads.phyla[1:2,]
hm.df <- reads.phyla[,-match("TaxaGroup",colnames(reads.phyla))]
# add melt.id
hm.df$phylum <- rownames(hm.df)
# sort data by row sums
hm.df <- hm.df[order(rowSums(hm.df[,1:6]), decreasing=T),]
hm.df <- hm.df[1:20,]
hm.df[1:3,]
##                 16S 18S trnL  ITS  COI COI-spun         phylum
## Proteobacteria 3862   3 2462   43 1163       75 Proteobacteria
## Basidiomycota     0 850    9 1644   21        1  Basidiomycota
## Ascomycota        2 765   43  971  451       53     Ascomycota

Draw a simply heatmap of read frequency in each phylumn, where melt.id=phylum defines the y-axis label in the heatmap:

ggHeatmap(hm.df, melt.id="phylum", verbose = F)

Set log.scale.colour=T to active logscale colour. Add a line to split the top 5 fom others:

Note: the deafult y.levels=c() makes y labels sorted by alphabetical order, but if y.levels=NA, there is no sorting applied.

hm <- ggHeatmap(hm.df, melt.id="phylum", y.levels=NA, log.scale.colour=T, verbose = F)
hm + ggAddLine(linetype=2, yintercept=5.5, colour="red")

The heatmap start to draw the rows from bottom to top as default, you can set y.levels=rev(rownames(hm.df)) to reverse the order of y labels, and set add.label=F to remove the numbers:

y.rev=rev(rownames(hm.df))
ggHeatmap(hm.df, melt.id="phylum", y.levels=y.rev, log.scale.colour=T, add.label=F, verbose = F)
